headline: US federal agents shoot dead another person in Minneapolis
description: A video circulating on social media – and confirmed by authorities – shows several agents, including at least one wearing a vest marked 'POLICE,' surrounding a person on the ground and hitting him multiple times. Several gunshots are heard.

Myanmar opens final phase of junta-run election as military allies head for landslide
description: The army-backed Union Solidarity and Development Party is poised for a sweeping victory in a vote critics say is tightly controlled by the junta and designed to entrench military rule nearly five years after the coup.

headline: Brave1, the online armory supplying Ukraine's troops, reveals the limits of its efficiency
description: The platform, which was created to boost defense sector innovation and offset Russia's material superiority, helped Ukrainian units quickly obtain supplies. However, it also risks reaching a cap of technological sophistication.

headline: Inside the workshop where dress forms are made
description: For 160 years, the French company Stockman has been handcrafting dress forms used by fashion designers, costume makers and aspiring stylists to refine their creations. This centuries-old expertise allows Stockman to meet custom requests from around the world.

headline: France is considering banning phones in high schools. This school near Paris already does.
description: The Lycée Michelet, a large school complex with 2,300 students, banned mobile phones in its hallways in April 2025. School officials report positive results from a decision made in agreement with the entire educational community.

'We were walking in blood': Iran's doctors recount crackdown on protesters
description: From crowded emergency rooms to apocalyptic scenes in Iranian cities, healthcare workers told Le Monde about the violence that descended on protesters calling for the end of the Iranian regime from January 8.

headline: An era of distrust emerges between the US and its Western allies
description: Donald Trump's suggestion that the US could seize Greenland by force has exposed the strategic isolation his administration has chosen, in disregard for the country's commitments. Even though the Republican president abandoned the idea at Davos, the damage to US credibility is substantial.

headline: How surveillance companies track smartphone users through advertising data
description: Companies are offering law enforcement agencies the ability to track smartphone users through advertising data gathered on their devices. Le Monde attended confidential presentations of these new surveillance tools to learn more.
